 Synchronous and Asynchronous programming refer to the way code executes and how it handles tasks that take time to complete. In JavaScript, these two programming paradigms differ in their approach to dealing with I/O (Input/Output) operations like fetching data from a server or reading files from the local storage.

Synchronous Programming:
In synchronous programming, a function completes its execution before returning control back to the caller. If a task takes time to complete, it blocks the main event loop of the JavaScript runtime environment until it's done. This means that no other tasks can be processed in parallel. An example of synchronous code using `fetch` could look like this:

```javascript
const getDataSync = async () => {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');
    const data = await response.json();
    console.log(`Synchronously fetched data: ${data}`);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  }
};
getDataSync(); // The main thread blocks here until the `fetch` is completed
```

As you can see in this example, we use async/await syntax to simplify asynchronous code. However, in a real-world scenario, it could still result in an unresponsive UI while waiting for the data from the server since the main event loop will be blocked. 

Asynchronous Programming:
In contrast, Asynchronous programming allows tasks that take time to complete to run concurrently with other code. This is achieved by using callbacks or promises (or nowadays mostly async/await) to handle the completion of asynchronous operations. In simple words, JavaScript keeps running while the data retrieval operation completes in parallel.

An example of asynchronous programming could look like this:

```javascript
const getDataAsync = () => {
  fetch('https://api.example.com/data')
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(data => console.log(`Asynchronously fetched data: ${data}`))
    .catch(error => console.error(error));
};
getDataAsync(); // The main thread continues execution immediately
```

The benefit of this approach is that the user interface doesn't get blocked while waiting for the server response. Asynchronous programming makes it possible to create responsive and more pleasant user experiences in JavaScript-powered applications, particularly on the web.

In summary, synchronous programming blocks the main thread until the asynchronous operation completes, whereas asynchronous programming allows other tasks to continue while waiting for the results of an I/O operation.
